1. Service Interface (UserService.java):

```java
public interface UserService {
  void updateMultipleRecords(List<User> data);
}
```

2. Service Implementation (UserServiceImpl.java):

```java
@Service
public class UserServiceImpl implements UserService {
  private final UserDao userDao;

  public UserServiceImpl(UserDao userDao) {
    this.userDao = userDao;
  }

  @Override
  public void updateMultipleRecords(List<User> data) {
    userDao.updateMultipleRecords(data);
  }
}
```

3. DAO Interface (UserDao.java):

```java
public interface UserDao {
  void updateMultipleRecords(List<User> data);
}
```

4. DAO Implementation (UserDaoImpl.java):

```java
@Repository
public class UserDaoImpl implements UserDao {
  @PersistenceContext
  private EntityManager entityManager;

  @Override
  public void updateMultipleRecords(List<User> data) {
    for (User user : data) {
      entityManager.merge(user);
    }
  }
}
```

In this example:
- `UserService` acts as an interface for business logic related to the User entity or model.
- `UserServiceImpl` is the implementation of the `UserService` interface and delegates the actual update operation to the `UserDao`.
- `UserDao` is an interface that defines data access-related operations for the User entity.
- `UserDaoImpl` is the implementation of the `UserDao` interface and performs the actual database operations using `EntityManager`.

Please adjust the class and package names, as well as the database operations, according to your project's requirements and entities.

If you want to use JDBC in your DAO implementation instead of JPA (EntityManager), you can modify the UserDaoImpl class accordingly. Here's an example:

